## **SECTION 1: REFLECTION ON PERFORMANCE AND OBJECTIVES**

### **1.1 Performance Against Objectives**

This quarter I delivered the BISS Test Automation Framework Modernisation — a complete refactor of 135+ legacy hard-coded test scenarios into a data-driven, self-healing BDD framework. The original objective was to eliminate manual test maintenance overhead and false-confidence placeholder assertions that were masking real bugs in a government payment-validation process.

I achieved this by consolidating 90+ copy-pasted login blocks into a shared Background, centralising 405 UI locators into one ObjectRepository, and building a two-database runtime herd resolver (DBRouter) that pulls live data from BISS_DATA and BISS_INET at startup. Tests no longer contain a single hard-coded value. The framework now ships with 6-layer resilience — smart waits, dropdown self-heal, expired-agent recovery, blacklist re-fetch, scenario retry, and soft assertions — so real-world flakes are handled automatically instead of halting the run.

On delivery: the framework went live on Jenkins/OpenShift in March. Nightly execution is active (22:00 Mon–Fri), and stakeholders receive pass/fail reports + evidence docs in their inbox automatically. The CI/CD pipeline is currently in progress with Patrick (DevOps), and once live, will add build-health trending visibility to leadership. Time saved: 6–9 hours per sprint, roughly 300 hours per year just in maintenance elimination and zero manual data prep.

