### **1.2 Performance Against CPD Level 2 Expectations**

**Self-Organisation:** I designed and led the entire modernisation solo over 8 weeks, breaking a large problem (brittle automation costing 4–6 hrs/sprint) into executable phases: framework core → ENTS/NRCISYF module → data extraction utility → reporting stack → resilience system → locator centralisation → CI/CD. Each phase built on the last with clear deliverables. I maintained clean/functional work practices throughout — ObjectRepository in version control, Hooks properly compartmentalised, no hardcoded values anywhere — and managed scope effectively by saying no to nice-to-haves and staying on the critical path.

**Problem Solving:** The core problem was layered. Legacy tests were brittle (placeholder assertions), data-coupled (hardcoded herds + Excel rows), repetitive (90+ login duplicates), and unmaintainable (50+ scattered files). I broke this into components: data resolution → test language → resilience → locator management → automation. Each required different solutions (DBRouter + HerdAgentExtractor, Gherkin refactoring, 6-layer recovery ladder, centralised ObjectRepository). When the SSO expired mid-run, I didn't just patch it — I built `Hooks.markAgentExpired()` + re-resolution logic so the framework self-recovers. When dropdowns rendered outside the DOM, I didn't hardcode a wait — I implemented mat-select self-heal with 3 fallback strategies.

**Initiative:** This work wasn't mandated. I identified the problem, quantified it (8 structural defects in the legacy suite), proposed a modern solution, and got buy-in from Patrick and the dev team. I took on full ownership and delivered without hand-holding. The framework now scales — new test modules (Staff portal, Overclaim, Dual Claim) reuse the same engine at near-zero cost, and I've documented it so the team can extend it without me.

**Interpersonal Skills:** I collaborated closely with Patrick on the Jenkins/OpenShift integration — explained requirements clearly, incorporated feedback on the Jenkinsfile, and handled the credential/permissions setup smoothly. I built the framework with the team in mind: business-language tests so analysts can confirm coverage without dev translation, shared Backgrounds so duplicates never creep back in, and a reporting stack so stakeholders see results automatically without asking "did it pass?"

**Adaptability:** When the legacy file was 135+ scenarios with 80+ commented-out lines per scenario, I adapted. Instead of a 1:1 refactor, I consolidated 25+ scenarios into single E2E flows and removed all dead code. When herd exhaustion was a real risk, I built fallback re-fetch with escalating DB limits (10 → 15 → 20 → 25). When the reporting was manual (30–45 min per run), I automated it — HTML dashboard, Word docs with embedded screenshots, JUnit XML for Jenkins, email summary.

**Teamwork:** I delivered a framework the whole team benefits from. Every test now uses shared locators, shared login, shared data resolution. I removed the bottleneck of "find me a valid herd" by building HerdAgentExtractor. I removed "update all the XPaths" by centralising 405 keys. I removed manual reporting by automating 4 output formats. The team no longer maintains spreadsheets or edits hardcoded values — they write tests that describe the business process.

